A l b e r t  M a r c k w a r d t ' s  t r a n s c r i p t i o n  c o l l a t e d  w i t h  B o d l e i a n  L i b r a r y  M s  S e l d e n  S u p r a  6 3

<section type="introduction">
<term lang="la">VOCABULARIUM SAXONICUM</term>

<term lang="oe">MID. hiht Ic &#254;olize.</term>
L.N.		
Laur. Nowel
1567

<term lang="oe">Butan hiht ic ahni&yogh;e.</term>
W.L.		
Will
Lombard

<term lang="oe">w&#230;cca&#254; &#254;ine leohtf&#230;t.</term>
W. L. 	

for the degrees of the declinati&omacron; of the old Inglishe, or Sax&omacron; tongue,

.1. reade the Lawes before the Conquest:
.2. the Sax&omacron; chr&omacron;. of peterborough, after the Conquest. 
.3. The Sax&omacron; writte of .H. 3. to oxfordshyre: in <expan type="">the</expan> litle booke of olde
Lawes, fo. 
.4. The pater n<expan type="">oster</expan> &#38; Crede, of Rob. Grosted: in the booke of patrices
purgatorie &#38;c. 
.5. The rythme of Jacob: in the booke called flos flor&umacron;.
.6. The Chronicles called Brute: Gower, Chaucier, &#38;c.

by the <expan type="">which</expan>, and suche like it may appeare, how, and by what
steps, our language is fallen fr&omacron; the old Inglishe, and drawen nearer
to the frenche: This may wel be lightened by shorte examples, 
taken fr&omacron; theise bookes, and is meete to be discouered when this
Dictionarie shalbe emprinted.

W. Lambarde.    
1570

W. L. ex Dono L. <term lang="la">Noelli auctoris
Invigila Lampadi.</term> <term lang="oe">W&#38;aeligcca&#254; &#254;ine leohtf&#230;.		
W. L. 1567
And wille h&amacron;m l&amacron;wyrhte;</term>
</section>

</page>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="oe">Bleost&#230;nin&yogh;.</form> <xpln lang="en" lexeme="almost(adv)" lexeme="altar(n)" lexeme="away(adv)" lexeme="cement(n)" lexeme="colour(n)" lexeme="die(n)" lexeme="durable(a)" lexeme="express(v)" lexeme="fine(a)" lexeme="floor(n)" lexeme="form(n)" lexeme="gross(a)" lexeme="high(a)" lexeme="Italy(pn)" lexeme="little(a)" lexeme="mosaic(a)" lexeme="ornament(n)" lexeme="paint(v)" lexeme="painting(n)" lexeme="picture(n)" lexeme="portray(v)" lexeme="reason(n)" lexeme="see(v)" lexeme="set(v)" lexeme="square(a)" lexeme="stone(n)" lexeme="take(v)" lexeme="thickness(n)" lexeme="together(adv)" lexeme="wall(n)" lexeme="washing(n)" lexeme="wearing(n)" lexeme="weather(n)" lexeme="Westminster(pn)" lexeme="work(n)">
Mosaicke woorkes,
<expan type="">whiche</expan> is a kinde of ornament
in picture made <expan type="">with</expan> little
square stones like dies of all
coulours sette togither <expan type="">with</expan> cer&#173;
tayne fine cyme<expan type="">en</expan>t upon a walle
or floore, so that the foormes
of thinges be there <expan type="">with</expan> pour&#173;
trayed &#38; expressed as though
they were paynted, &#38; it is more
durable than any other kind of
paynting by reason that neyther
by wear<expan type="">in</expan>g, wether, nor wassh&#173;
ing, the colour can be taken
away, <expan type="">whiche</expan> hath the thick&#173;
nesse of the litle dies wher<expan type="">with</expan>
the woorke is made. Of this
kinde of woorke is litle in Eng&#173;
land, howbeit I have seen of it,
especially upon churche floores
before altares, as is to be seen
before the high altare at West&#173;
minster, although it be but
grosse. In Italie it is almost
every where.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="oe">Corsned.</form> <xpln lang="en" lexeme="cursebread(n)" lexeme="certain(a)" lexeme="consecrated(a)" lexeme="bread(n)" lexeme="barley(n)" lexeme="use(v)" lexeme="give(v)" lexeme="accuse(v)" lexeme="heinous(a)" lexeme="crime(n)" lexeme="great(a)" lexeme="presumption(n)" lexeme="witness(n)" lexeme="deny(v)" lexeme="oath(n)" lexeme="opinion(n)" lexeme="guilty(a)" lexeme="able(a)" lexeme="swallow(v)" lexeme="ceremonious(a)" lexeme="clear(a)" lexeme="receive(v)" lexeme="harm(n)" lexeme="ordinary(a)" lexeme="examination(n)" lexeme="suspected(a)" lexeme="person(n)" lexeme="even(adv)" lexeme="like(a)" lexeme="manner(n)" lexeme="ordeal(n)" lexeme="speak(v)" lexeme="place(n)">Cursebread. Certayne
consecrated bread of barlye
used to be given to suche as
being accused of heynouse
crimes upon great <expan type="">pre</expan>sumptions
&#38; (yet no certain witnesse) de&#173;
nied the same by othe. And the
opinion was that it they were
gyltie, they shuld not be hable to
swalowe this cerimoniouse bread
&#38; if they were cleare, they
shulde receave none harme
therof. It was an ordinarie
kinde of examination of suche
suspected personnes even in like
manner as the Ordal was, wher&#173;
of we shall speake in place.
It was sometyme likewise done
in consecrated cheese.</xpln>
<lemenote>
A word, "cursebread," not found in OED.
</lemenote>
</wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="oe">Gl&#230;stin&yogh;abyrin&yogh;.</form> <xpln lang="en" lexeme="Glastonbury(pn)" lexeme="call(v)" lexeme="British(a)" lexeme="William Malmesbury(pn)" lexeme="say(v)" lexeme="Ynnis Witrin(pn)" lexeme="apple(n)" lexeme="glass(n)" lexeme="Ynnis Avalon(pn)" lexeme="island(n)" lexeme="inhabited(a)" lexeme="disciple(n)" lexeme="Philip(n)" lexeme="apostle(n)" lexeme="send(v)" lexeme="France(pn)" lexeme="preach(v)" lexeme="Christ(pn)" lexeme="Briton(n)" lexeme="number(n)" lexeme="Joseph of Aramathie(pn)" lexeme="build(v)" lexeme="church(n)" lexeme="monastery(n)" lexeme="abbey(n)" lexeme="sith(adv)" lexeme="newly(adv)" lexeme="erect(v)" lexeme="Ine(pn)" lexeme="king(n)" lexeme="Wessex(pn)" lexeme="destroy(v)" lexeme="Dane(n)" lexeme="repair(v)" lexeme="Saint Dunston(pn)" lexeme="time(n)" lexeme="grow(v)" lexeme="richest(a)" lexeme="famous(a)" lexeme="Englond(pn)">Glastenburie,

li<expan type="">am</expan> Malmesburie sayth Ynnis

Glasse, or Ynnis Avalon, the
Ilond of Apples. Was first en&#173;
habited by the 12 disciples of
Philippe the Apostle, sent by
h<expan type="">im</expan> out of Fra<expan type="">un</expan>ce to preache
Christe to the Brytons, who, one
of their n<expan type="">um</expan>ber being Joseph
of Aramathie, builded there a
churche or monasterie. The
abbey was sith newly erected by
Ine, king of Westsex, a<expan type="">nno</expan> 722
&#38; since being destroyed by the
Danes it was repayred by <expan type="">Saint</expan>.
Dunstone &#38; in time grewe to
the richest &#38; most famouse

Scotland is
s<expan type="">um</expan>time signified therby as
likewise Irel<expan type="">an</expan>d is called Scot&#173;
land &#38; Scotia major in old
writers. The cause of this c<expan type="">on</expan>&#173;
fusion is that the Irisshe men &#38;
Scottes are but one nation, of
one tung &#38; nature &#38; maner of
liv<expan type="">in</expan>g. The very true &#38; a<expan type="">un</expan>&#173;
ci<expan type="">en</expan>t name of both these people
is Scottes, by <expan type="">whiche</expan> name they
were called before they came
into eyther co<expan type="">un</expan>trey, if <expan type="">our</expan>r his&#173;
tories be herin to be beleaved.
They first inhabited Ireland,
<expan type="">whiche</expan> was aunci<expan type="">en</expan>tly &#38; before
their c<expan type="">um</expan>m<expan type="">ing</expan> there called <term lang="oe">Hy&#173;
bernia &#38; Ierne</term> <term lang="gk">&#x1F30;&#x03AD;&#x03C1;&#x03BD;&#x03B7;</term> whereof
we calle it <term lang="oe">Iernland</term> or <term lang="oe">Irland</term> by
c<expan type="">on</expan>traction &#38; they th<expan type="">em</expan> selves
calle it <term lang="oe">Iren</term> to this daye. <expan type="">Ou</expan>r
auncient writers called it <term lang="oe">Scot&#173;
land</term> bycause it was enhabited
by Scottes. Howbeit in the
meane season they forget no
the old name <expan type="">whiche</expan> hath of
later dayes so <expan type="">pre</expan>valed that it
hath cha<expan type="">un</expan>ged the name also of 
the inhabit<expan type="">an</expan>tes, who, forget&#173;
t<expan type="">ing</expan> that ever they were Scottes,

</page>

<page fol="87v">
calle th<expan type="">em</expan> selves <term lang="oe">Irenogh,</term> that
is Irishmen, of the co<expan type="">un</expan>trey
<expan type="">whiche</expan> they enhabite. On the
other side, wheras the same
Scottes not long after their
c<expan type="">um</expan>ming into Ireland passed
the Strayt of Kentire &#38; enter&#173;
<expan type="">ing</expan> into the north part of Bry&#173;
tane, than called <term lang="oe">Albanie,</term> by
litle &#38; litle drave out the
Pightes, than enhabit<expan type="">an</expan>tes ther&#173;
of &#38; possessed the same th<expan type="">em</expan>
selves. We of th<expan type="">em</expan>, being as
we calle th<expan type="">em</expan> Irisshe men, used
to calle the co<expan type="">un</expan>trey <term lang="oe">Ireland,</term>
howe beit the name of Scottes
hath in time there more <expan type="">pre</expan>&#173;
valed so that it is nowe <expan type="">with</expan>
one c<expan type="">on</expan>sent of all nations called
<term lang="oe">Scotland,</term> sav<expan type="">in</expan>g of th<expan type="">em</expan> selves
who calle it <term lang="oe">Albanogh</term> by the
aunci<expan type="">en</expan>t name.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="oe">Ordal.</form> <xpln lang="en">A kinde of judgem<expan type="">en</expan>t &#38;

water &#38; fire. Eche of <expan type="">whiche</expan>
was in two sortes also, the first
by hote water that should eyther
scald the gyltie or not hurt the
innoc<expan type="">en</expan>t; the seconde that shoul
eyther receyve or cast up the
accused, being let downe into
the same colde. The firie ordal
was eyther by goinge up<expan type="">on</expan>
barres of hoate ir<expan type="">on</expan> barefoted
or by caryinge sume certein
weight of hoate iron hare band&#173;
ed by certein spaces. The cere&#173;
monie &#38; circ<expan type="">um</expan>stance of eyther
appeareth in my table to the
translati<expan type="">on</expan> of the Saxon lawes.
It toke the name of the effect
for it signifieth <term lang="la">expers quasi
criminis expers,</term> innocent of the
crime, as having no part at all
therin. Quasi, <term lang="oe">Ord&#339;l</term></xpln></wordentry>

<page fol="128v">
<wordentry type="h"><form lang="oe">Scotta.</form> <xpln lang="en">A Scotte. It signifieth
a shooter, wherof the Scottes
had their name &#38; to this daye
the Redde shankes are excell<expan type="">en</expan>t
archers. They came out of
Irel<expan type="">an</expan>d into Scotl<expan type="">an</expan>d where
driv<expan type="">in</expan>g out the Pightes, a<expan type="">un</expan>&#173;
ci<expan type="">en</expan>t inhabit<expan type="">an</expan>tes of the same,
they posessed the whole coun&#173;
trey, wherby we have let the old
name of Albanie &#38; calle it
Scotl<expan type="">an</expan>d, howbeit the Scottes
th<expan type="">em</expan> selves called (it) yet
Albanogh.</xpln></wordentry>

<wordentry type="h"><form lang="oe">Scotland.</form> <xpln lang="en">The co<expan type="">un</expan>trey of the
Scottes, by <expan type="">whiche</expan> name in
times passed we signified Ire&#173;
l<expan type="">an</expan>d, howbeit in time the old
name hath take place, &#38; on the
other side we have left the
a<expan type="">un</expan>cient name of Scotl<expan type="">an</expan>d,
<expan type="">whiche</expan> is Albanie &#38; calle it
after the name of the inhabi&#173;
t<expan type="">an</expan>tes. See more of this matter
in Irel<expan type="">an</expan>d.</xpln></wordentry>
